1. Load required libraries

2. NBumi

The Michaelis-Menten equation fits full-transcript single-cell RNASeq data well, but often struggles to fit data tagged with unique molecular identifiers (UMIs). This is a result of UMI datasets typically not being sequenced to saturation, thus many dropouts are a result of low sequencing coverage rather than a failure of reverse transcription. To account for zeros resulting from insufficient sequencing depth, the M3Drop packaged includes a depth-adjusted negative binomial model (DANB). DANB models each observation as a negative binomial distribution with mean proportional to the mean expression of the respective gene and the relative sequencing depth of the respective cell. The dispersion parameter of the negative binomial is fit to the variance of each gene.

2.1 10X Chromium

2.1.1 Load in the 10X counts matrix

# Set the work directory
setwd(dirname(rstudioapi::getActiveDocumentContext()$path))

# 10X Chromium
counts_10X <- read.csv("./tables/10X_counts_matrix.csv",
                       row.names = 1,
                       header=T)

count_mat_10X <- NBumiConvertData(counts_10X, is.counts=TRUE)
## [1] "Removing  168 undetected genes."
DANB_fit_10X <- NBumiFitModel(count_mat_10X)

2.1.2 Check the goodness of fit

# Smoothed gene-specific variances
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
stats_10X <- NBumiCheckFitFS(count_mat_10X, DANB_fit_10X)

# print(c(stats_10X$gene_error,stats_10X$cell_error))

2.1.3 use a binomial test to evaluable the significance of features under the DANB model:

NBDropFS_10X <- NBumiFeatureSelectionCombinedDrop(DANB_fit_10X, method="fdr",
                                                  qval.thres=0.05,
                                                  suppress.plot=F)
